liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian sharemarket has finished higher for the day despite trending lower through the session, gaining 0.1% to close at 7,076 points. Looking at the sectors, tech stocks were the best performing sector, picking up 1.4% at the close. Utilities gained 1%, while real estate picked up 0.9%, and energy and consumer non-cyclicals were up 0.8% each. Only three sectors finished in the red — basic materials (-0.8%), industrials (-0.4%) and financials (-0.2%). Qantas also finished the day down 1.5% to $5.23, after warning rising fuel costs may hit fares. As for the top performers of the day: Paladin Energy +6.1% TechnologyOne +4% Whitehaven Coal +3.4% Megaport +3.3% Polynovo +3.3% And the worst performers for the day: Chalice Mining -5.1% Bellevue Gold -3.4% Allkem -3.3% Atlas Arteria -3.2% Sandfire Resources -3.2%
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ASX closes 0.1pc higher after tech stocks rally

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's all got to do with the falling price of iron ore futures. They've taken a hit in response to weaker-than-expected steel consumption, completion of pre-holiday restocking and possible output restrictions. On the Singapore Exchange, benchmark October iron ore was 3.2% lower at $117.25 a tonne. Several factors have jointly contributed to the broad weakness in raw materials, said Pei Hao, a Shanghai-based analyst at international brokerage firm FIS. "It becomes increasingly clear that demand has hit the ceiling amid weaker-than-expected steel sales for September and October, and after the replenishment of raw materials to meet production needs over the upcoming week-long holiday break came to an end," he said. Weighing on prices of the key steelmaking ingredient are also "concerns of tighter monetary policy", analysts at ANZ bank said in a note. — with Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Why are miners being dragged down on the market today?
